The expression nota domesticae turpitudinis differs in meaning from privatarum rerum dedecus: the former relates to moral or immoral domestic life, the latter to all private actions as op- posed to those that affect a man’s public character. Nota is applied (1) to the brand on cattle; Virg. Georg. 3, 158: (2) to the mark placed on a fugitive slave when retaken: (3) to the mark placed by the censor (nota cen-soria) on revising the list of citizens, opposite the name of the person degraded.
